{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6a8a77b5-e0fd-4716-8bee-44b53b73afd3","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **implicit span conversions** — `T[]` now implicitly converts to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This changes overload resolution:\n\n| .NET 9 (C# 13) | .NET 10 (C# 14) |\n|---|---|\n| `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` | `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` ✅ preferred |\n\nThe `MemoryExtensions` overload wins because `int[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<int>` is a more specific conversion than `int[]` → `IEnumerable<int>`.\n\nThe expression tree interpreter cannot handle `ReadOnlySpan<T>` (a `ref struct`), so it throws at runtime.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nDisambiguate by forcing the `Enumerable` overload. Either approach works:\n\n```csharp\n// Option 1: call Enumerable.Contains explicitly\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n\n// Option 2: cast away the array type so the span overload doesn't apply\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nBoth prevent the compiler from picking the `MemoryExtensions` span-based overload and keep the expression tree representable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b7ebf15d-cd32-4440-9eb6-be673297cceb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when compiled with `preferInterpretation: true`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), which changes how extension methods are resolved.\n\nBut more specifically, the issue here is likely related to how `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<T>()` is resolved for arrays.\n\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering 